            <section class="mt-8 prose">
              <h2>How this molding calculator works</h2>
              <p>
                This molding calculator is designed to cover the most common
                trim projects in one place:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>Baseboard and crown molding around a room</li>
                <li>Picture frame molding (wall boxes)</li>
                <li>Wainscoting with panels, stiles, and rails</li>
                <li>Curved or radius molding for arches and round walls</li>
              </ul>

              <h3>1. Room perimeter (baseboard and crown)</h3>
              <p>For straight runs of molding, the calculator:</p>
              <ol>
                <li>Adds up all wall lengths to get the total perimeter.</li>
                <li>Applies your chosen waste percentage.</li>
                <li>
                  Divides by the standard stick length to estimate how many
                  pieces to buy.
                </li>
              </ol>

              <div class="formula-box">
                <p><strong>Perimeter</strong></p>
                <p>\(\text{Perimeter} = L_1 + L_2 + \dots + L_n\)</p>
                <p><strong>With waste</strong></p>
                <p>
                  \(\text{Total with waste} = \text{Perimeter} \times \left(1 +
                  \dfrac{\text{Waste \%}}{100}\right)\)
                </p>
                <p><strong>Number of sticks</strong></p>
                <p>
                  \(\text{Sticks} = \left\lceil \dfrac{\text{Total with
                  waste}}{\text{Stick length}} \right\rceil\)
                </p>
              </div>

              <p>
                Use a higher waste factor (15–20%) if you have many short
                pieces, complicated corners, or are new to trim work.
              </p>

              <h3>2. Picture frame molding (wall boxes)</h3>
              <p>
                For picture frame molding, each box is treated as a simple
                rectangle:
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p><strong>Box perimeter</strong></p>
                <p>
                  \(\text{Box perimeter} = 2 \times (\text{Box width} +
                  \text{Box height})\)
                </p>
                <p><strong>Total molding</strong></p>
                <p>
                  \(\text{Total length} = \text{Box perimeter} \times
                  \text{Boxes per wall} \times \text{Number of walls}\)
                </p>
              </div>
              <p>The calculator can either:</p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  Use your specified box width and spacing to auto-fit boxes
                  across the wall, or
                </li>
                <li>
                  Use a fixed number of boxes and adjust spacing accordingly.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h3>3. Wainscoting panels</h3>
              <p>
                For wainscoting, the wall is divided into repeating panels
                separated by vertical stiles and bounded by rails.
              </p>
              <p>The calculator:</p>
              <ol>
                <li>Subtracts end margins from the total wall length.</li>
                <li>
                  Estimates how many panels fit based on your target panel width
                  and stile width.
                </li>
                <li>Adjusts the actual panel width so panels fit evenly.</li>
                <li>Computes total vertical and horizontal trim length.</li>
              </ol>

              <div class="formula-box">
                <p><strong>Effective wall length</strong></p>
                <p>
                  \(L_\text{eff} = L_\text{wall} - 2 \times \text{End margin}\)
                </p>
                <p><strong>Approximate panel count</strong></p>
                <p>
                  \(N \approx \dfrac{L_\text{eff} + \text{Stile
                  width}}{\text{Target panel width} + \text{Stile width}}\)
                </p>
                <p>
                  Then \(N\) is rounded to the nearest whole number and the
                  actual panel width is recomputed so everything fits.
                </p>
              </div>

              <h3>4. Curved and radius molding</h3>
              <p>
                For curved molding, the key is the arc length. For a circular
                arc:
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p><strong>Arc length</strong></p>
                <p>\(\text{Arc length} = r \times \theta\)</p>
                <p>
                  where \(r\) is the radius and \(\theta\) is the central angle
                  in radians.
                </p>
                <p>To convert degrees to radians:</p>
                <p>
                  \(\theta_\text{rad} = \theta_\text{deg} \times
                  \dfrac{\pi}{180}\)
                </p>
                <p><strong>Full circle</strong></p>
                <p>\(\text{Circumference} = 2 \pi r\)</p>
              </div>
              <p>
                Use the arc length result to order flexible molding or to cut
                kerfed wood strips for bending.
              </p>

              <h2>Practical tips for buying and installing molding</h2>
              <h3>Choose a realistic waste factor</h3>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>10%</strong> – simple room, few corners, experienced
                  installer.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>15%</strong> – average room, some obstacles, typical
                  DIY project.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>20%+</strong> – complex layout, lots of short pieces,
                  or premium profiles where matching grain matters.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h3>Stick length vs. handling</h3>
              <p>
                Longer sticks reduce joints but are harder to transport and
                maneuver:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>8 ft (2.44 m)</strong> – easy to handle in small rooms
                  and vehicles.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>12–16 ft (3.66–4.88 m)</strong> – better for long
                  walls and fewer seams, but may require a truck or trailer.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h3>Accounting for doors and windows</h3>
              <p>
                This calculator assumes continuous runs. For more precision:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>Subtract door widths from baseboard runs.</li>
                <li>
                  Decide whether molding runs behind or terminates at window
                  casings.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Plan separate pieces for each side of openings to minimize
                  visible joints.
                </li>
              </ul>
            </section>

            <section class="mt-8 prose">
              <h2>FAQ</h2>

              <h3>How do I use this calculator for crown molding?</h3>
              <p>
                Use the <strong>Room Perimeter</strong> tab. Measure each wall
                at the ceiling line, enter the lengths, choose a waste factor
                (usually 15%), and select the stick length your supplier
                carries. The calculator will give you total linear feet and how
                many sticks to buy.
              </p>

              <h3>Should I measure along the floor or ceiling?</h3>
              <p>
                For baseboards, measure along the floor. For crown molding,
                measure along the ceiling. In most rectangular rooms the
                difference is small, but in older houses with out-of-square
                walls, measuring where the molding will actually sit is more
                accurate.
              </p>

              <h3>Can I mix different molding profiles in one project?</h3>
              <p>
                Yes. Many designs use a combination of baseboard, chair rail,
                picture frame molding, and crown. Use this calculator separately
                for each profile and keep the results organized by type when you
                order materials.
              </p>

              <h3>How close will these estimates be?</h3>
              <p>
                The math is exact for the dimensions you enter, but real-world
                factors like out-of-square corners, bad cuts, and material
                defects mean you should always buy a bit extra. That is why the
                waste percentage is so important. When in doubt, round up one
                extra stick.
              </p>
            </section>
